content.problemStatement:
The **`if-else if` ladder** in C is a sequence of **multiple `if` and `else if`** statements that allow you to test several conditions in sequence.
It is used when you need to check multiple conditions, but only the first true condition will execute its block of code. The `else` block at the end serves as the default, executed when none of the conditions are true.

**Syntax:**

```c
if (condition1) {
    // Executes if condition1 is true
} else if (condition2) {
    // Executes if condition2 is true
} else if (condition3) {
    // Executes if condition3 is true
} else {
    // Executes if none of the above conditions are true
}
```

---

**Example:**

```c
#include

int main() {
    int number = 50;

    // Using if-else if ladder to check the range of the number
    if (number >= 90) {
        printf("Excellent\n");
    } else if (number >= 70) {
        printf("Good\n");
    } else if (number >= 50) {
        printf("Average\n");
    } else {
        printf("Needs Improvement\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Expected Output:**

```default
Average
```

